## 10. Target Package Boundary Rules

### Add a file to `apps/frontend` when:

- it renders UI
- it manages frontend state
- it talks to Tauri IPC
- it talks to FastAPI over HTTP/SSE
- it is only used by the frontend app

### Add a file to `services/agent` when:

- it handles API routes
- it implements agent behavior
- it talks to providers
- it executes tools
- it persists sessions/events
- it owns permissions or approvals

### Add a file to `apps/desktop` when:

- it is native desktop shell logic
- it registers Tauri commands
- it manages secure local storage
- it supervises bundled binaries
- it enforces workspace scope at the native boundary

### Add a file to `crates/hotpath` when:

- it is native-performance logic
- it is reusable from Rust CLI/library
- it is not product UI or API orchestration

### Add a file to `packages/shared-types` when:

- it describes a public API/event/data contract
- both frontend and backend need the shape
- schema generation can keep language outputs aligned

### Add a file to `scripts` when:

- it is build/release/dev automation
- it is not runtime application code
- it is not a long-lived service

### Add a file to `doc` when:

- it is planning
- it is architecture
- it is feature design
- it is implementation notes
- it guides future agents or engineers

### Add a file to `testsprite_tests` when:

- it is generated by TestSprite or similar tooling
- it is an imported product test artifact
- it is not yet curated as normal CI E2E

